                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x53.png",
                "caption": "Figure 11:Quantitative evaluation of generated samples over 10,000 training iterations for varying values ofλ\\lambda. We report HPSv2 (left), PickScore (middle), and ImageReward (right). Higher scores indicate better alignment with human preferences.",
                "position": 4035
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x54.png",
                "caption": "Figure 12:Qualitative comparison on Random Inpainting.We compare one-step VFM samples against seven baselines. VFM recovers fine details and texture consistent with the unmasked regions, while maintaining high perceptual quality.",
                "position": 4073
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x55.png",
                "caption": "Figure 13:Qualitative comparison on Box Inpainting.Comparison of VFM against baselines for large occlusions. VFM generates plausible semantic content to fill the missing regions in a single step.",
                "position": 4076
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x56.png",
                "caption": "Figure 14:Qualitative comparison on Super-Resolution (×4\\times 4).VFM effectively upsamples the low-resolution inputs, leading to sharp edges and realistic textures compared to the often over-smoothed baseline results.",
                "position": 4079
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x57.png",
                "caption": "Figure 15:Qualitative comparison on Gaussian Deblurring.VFM successfully restores sharpness from heavily blurred observations (σ=3.0\\sigma=3.0), and it also avoids the artifacts common in guidance-based methods.",
                "position": 4082
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x58.png",
                "caption": "Figure 16:Qualitative comparison on Motion Deblurring.Comparison of deblurring performance on motion-blurred inputs. VFM resolves the motion streaks into coherent structures.",
                "position": 4085
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x59.png",
                "caption": "Figure 17:Visualizing the Learned Noise Space.We visualize the outputs of the noise adapterqϕ​(z|y)q_{\\phi}(z|y). From left to right: ground truth, measurement, the predicted latent meanμ\\mu, standard deviationσ\\sigma, and three independent latent samples drawn from the distribution. The visible structure in the “noise” confirms that the adapter optimizes the latent initialization to align with the conditional data manifold. From top to bottom, rows correspond to: random inpainting, box inpainting, super-resolution, gaussian deblurring, and motion deblurring.",
                "position": 4088
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x60.png",
                "caption": "Figure 18:Posterior Uncertainty Quantification.We display the pixel-wise mean and standard deviation computed from 10 conditional samples generated by VFM. The standard deviation maps (right column) accurately capture the uncertainty inherent in the inverse problem, which highlights ambiguous regions where the model generates diverse solutions.",
                "position": 4091
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x61.png",
                "caption": "Figure 19:Unconditional Samples.Curated unconditional samples generated by the VFM.",
                "position": 4094
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x62.png",
                "caption": "Figure 20:Posterior Diversity (Sample Set 1).Evaluation of sample diversity on gaussian deblurring. While baselines often collapse to a single mode or fail to produce valid results, VFM generates eight distinct, plausible, and measurement-consistent posterior samples.",
                "position": 4097
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x63.png",
                "caption": "Figure 21:Posterior Diversity (Sample Set 2).Additional examples of diverse posterior sampling on box inpainting task. The high variance among the VFM samples reflects the multimodal nature of the posterior distribution for these ill-posed tasks.",
                "position": 4100
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x64.png",
                "caption": "Figure 22:Uncurated Samples from Reward Fine-Tuning (λ=1\\lambda=1).Additional uncurated samples generated by the fine-tuned flow map. VFM consistently samples high-quality images from the target reward-tilted distribution, resulting in enhanced aesthetic and perceptual quality in a single forward pass.",
                "position": 4103
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07276/2603.07276v1/x65.png",
                "caption": "Figure 23:Evolution of One-Step Generations during Reward Fine-Tuning.We visualize the progress of generated samples across varying fine-tuning iterations using fixed latent seeds, all produced in a single neural function evaluation (1 NFE). These seeds are drawn from a pure standard Gaussian distribution. Although we tilt the original flow map to accommodate adapter-conditioned noises, the original noise space remains valid. As a result, this short fine-tuning process successfully enhances the one-step generative capabilities of the base DMF model even without the use of an adapter.",
                "position": 4106
            }
